<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="596" pageId="4" pageNumber="595" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[714,1247,1348,1667]" lastBlockId="5.[151,684,1156,1232]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="596" pageId="4" pageNumber="595">DIAGNOSIS. — Dorsal surface covered with imbricated scales with distinct primary plates. The oral shields are small in relation to the size of the disk. Robust, erect infradental papilla; the second oral papilla is narrow and pointed; the distal is the largest, leaf-shaped, erect, with an acute extremity. The dorsal spines are the smallest. Two tentacle scales: the internal scale is slightly larger and supported on the ventral arm plate, and the external is supported on the lateral arm plate.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
